Docker runs the container in the foreground.

You see logs/output directly in your terminal.

You canâ€™t type other commands until you stop it (usually with Ctrl + C).

âœ… Use -d when:
You want the container to keep running in the background.

Youâ€™re running web servers, databases, or long-lived applications.

You donâ€™t need to see real-time logs immediately.

